snippet.textDisplay:
You guys never cease to amaze me with the things that you've
done and the wonderful experiences of places you’ve gone and things that you’ve
seen. I’m a 54-year-old man who has been with the same woman for 35 years.
Though we have lived a good life with our three kids, we have always been
cautious about spending money, thusly, there’s been a lot of things that we’ve
wanted to do but haven’t. Then, about four years ago, my wife was diagnosed
with stage 3 going into stage 4 cancer. My company fired me the day after she
started treatment with no explanation, simply saying, “We don’t have time to go
into it”. Wow, though I was scared for our future, we never looked back, only
forward. We have always been involved with our community, helping people who
needed it on their farm or in their homes, coaching kids sports and serving as
a Cub Master. Suddenly, people began showing up at our door with money, and
food and lots of love. We learned that Lasagna is about the most popular food
that people will bring which was fine with us. It freezes well, reheats well,
and can be eaten for breakfast, lunch or dinner. We were so blessed and in
sooooo many ways.   – So, my wife, Karen,
has now been cancer free for almost 2 years and early last spring, 2019, she
shocked the heck out of me while at the dinner table. She asked me and the kids
that, if we could go anywhere in the world on vacation, where would it be. Long
story short, we have cashed in and squeezed out just about every cent we have
and are going on a two-week vacation in Hawaii, one week of that being on a
cruise. Many years ago, I promised her that one day, I would sing a song to her
on a beach at sunset. About 8 months ago I bought an Ukulele and I hope to sing
Perfect by Ed Sheeran to her. My only fear is that I will burst into tears and
not be able to sing or play. You see, this woman who doesn’t have a mean bone
in her body is the love of my life and without her, I would be lost. So, talk
about stepping outside your comfort zone, my hopes are to spend the rest of our
day creating enough memories and laughter to make up for things that we should
have done long ago. I’m sorry that this is so long but, I mean, I get what you
guys are about and want to share with the world this message… “Life is tooooooo
short, live it while you can because none of us know if there is going to be a
tomorrow. Love, Laugh, Live. Be kind to one another…” “Seek discomfort” – Anyway,
thank you guys for who you are and how you inspire others. I hope that you
never lose sight of that and that you’ll continue to be blessed enough to always
do what you do. For us, for now, Hawaii, here we come. God bless

snippet.textDisplay:
So, let me summarize how to save the world:
1) use reef-safe sunscreen
2) use reusable bottles (filled with water from what source? A plastic bottle?) and bamboo cutlery
3) buy a poncho at a local store
and of course, most importantly,
4) carbon-offset the thousands of miles you fly (it always helps for a good conscience to donate for planting some trees at some point in the future that will then grow and absorb CO2 from the atmosphere in a few years or decades)
5) drive around in big vans and jeeps the whole time.

Oh, one more thing, where is the Seek Discomfort clothing produced?
